<div class="mb-requirement-container">
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-14072">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> </span>
      <b>NOTE: </b>Check out the Digital Resource Guide for the Citizenship in
      the Nation merit badge
      <a
        href="https://www.scouting.org/skills/merit-badges/digital-resource-guides/citizenship-nation/"
        target="_blank"
        >HERE</a
      >
      for information and helpful resources to engage your learning and assist
      you along on your merit badge journey!<br />
      The official merit badge pamphlets are now free and downloadable
      <a
        href="https://filestore.scouting.org/filestore/Merit_Badge_ReqandRes/Pamphlets/Citizenship%20in%20the%20Nation.pdf"
        target="_blank"
        >HERE</a
      >
      or can be purchased at the
      <a href="https://www.scoutshop.org/" target="_blank ">Scout Shop.</a>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-10141">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 1. </span>
      What is the Constitution of the United States? What does the Constitution
      do? What principles does it reflect? Why is it important to have a
      Constitution? <br /><i>Resources:</i>
      <a
        href="https://vimeo.com/1157341979/58d0d206c3?fl=pl&amp;fe=vl"
        target="_blank"
        >Creating the Constitution (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/vHm_b7QOc7U" target="_blank"
        >What Is Federalism? | Things Explained (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/XfS-bZ69p0E" target="_blank"
        >Walkthrough of the Constitution | Constitution 101 (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/R2h8CrX84Eo" target="_blank"
        >The Bill of Rights (video)</a
      >
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-10130">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 2. </span>
      List the six purposes for creating the United States Constitution set
      forth in the Preamble to the Constitution. How do these purposes affect
      your family and community? <br /><i>Resources:</i>
      <a href="https://youtu.be/eLQ3ZEnchB4" target="_blank"
        >What Does the Preamble Actually Mean? (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/nXh2lEk2XNs" target="_blank"
        >What Is Ratification? (video)</a
      >
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-10145">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 3. </span>
      List the three branches of the United States government. Explain:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10145 mb-requirement-id-10147">
        (a) The function of each branch of government <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/hltv8-nzcUc" target="_blank"
          >What Is the Legislative Branch of the U.S. Government? (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://www.senate.gov/" target="_blank">US Senate (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://www.house.gov/" target="_blank"
          >US House of Representatives (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/BWR2p9j9hWo" target="_blank"
          >What Is the Executive Branch of the U.S. Government? (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/n_3cBWrC5n8" target="_blank"
          >What Is Veto Power? (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/9giPmCWnepU" target="_blank"
          >What Is the Judicial Branch of the U.S. Government? (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://www.supremecourt.gov/" target="_blank"
          >Supreme Court of the United States (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/8Zpe046BxQw" target="_blank"
          >The US Court System Explained (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10145 mb-requirement-id-10148">
        (b) Why it is important to divide powers among different branches
        <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/TAqAvKnheSk" target="_blank"
          >The Separation of Powers (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10145 mb-requirement-id-10149">
        (c) How each branch checks and balances the others <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/JaYA3cLPMc4" target="_blank"
          >Checks and Balances/Separation of Powers Explained (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10145 mb-requirement-id-10150">
        (d) How citizens can be involved in each branch of government <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/R8yrjKj4cP0" target="_blank"
          >Political Participation and Elections (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/a2-QL59pVRo" target="_blank"
          >The Duties and Responsibilities of Citizens (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://ymcacona.org/" target="_blank"
          >YMCA Youth Conference on National Affairs (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://nextgenamerica.org/who-we-are/" target="_blank"
          >NextGen America (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.youthrights.org/about/our-movement/"
          target="_blank"
          >National Youth Rights Association (website)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-10143">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 4. </span>
      Discuss the importance of:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10143 mb-requirement-id-10151">
        (a) <i>Declaration of Independence</i> <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/faa5YMquv_8" target="_blank"
          ><i>The Declaration of Independence</i> (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10143 mb-requirement-id-10152">
        (b) <i>Bill of Rights</i> (the first 10 Amendments to the Constitution)
        and the 14th Amendment <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/yYEfLm5dLMQ" target="_blank"
          >A 3-Minute Guide to the <i>Bill of Rights</i> (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/ftoroDlR4Ss" target="_blank"
          >The 14th Amendment (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10143 mb-requirement-id-10153">
        (c) E Pluribus Unum, the traditional United States motto <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/ki23hxGovao" target="_blank"
          >What Does E Pluribus Unum Actually Mean? (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-10142">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 5. </span>
      Watch the national evening news for five days in a row or read the main
      stories in a national media organization (e.g., a newspaper or news
      website) for five days in a row. Discuss the national issues that you
      learned about with your counselor. Choose one issue and explain how it
      affects you, your family, and community. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
      <a
        href="https://filestore.scouting.org/filestore/Merit_Badge_ReqandRes/Requirement%20Resources/Citizenship%20in%20the%20Nation/Media%20Tracking%20Planner.docx"
        target="_blank"
        >Tracking Planner (PDF)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://www.snopes.com/factbot/" target="_blank"
        >Factbot (website)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://www.factcheck.org/" target="_blank"
        >FactCheck (website)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://apnews.com/" target="_blank">AP News (website)</a><br />
      <a href="https://www.politifact.com/" target="_blank"
        >Politifact (website)</a
      >
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-10144">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 6. </span>
      With your counselor's approval, choose a speech of national historical
      importance. Explain: <br /><i>Resources:</i>
      <a href="https://youtu.be/vP4iY1TtS3s" target="_blank"
        >I Have a Dream Speech by Martin Luther King Jr. (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/lK8gYGg0dkE" target="_blank"
        >President Franklin D. Roosevelt Declares War on Japan Speech (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/uSHGXVBA17A" target="_blank"
        >"Tear Down This Wall" Reagan Speech June 12 1987 (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://www.jstor.org/" target="_blank"
        >Explore the World's Knowledge, Cultures, and Ideas (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://www.americanrhetoric.com/" target="_blank"
        >American Rhetoric (website)</a
      ><br />
      <a
        href="https://www.americanrhetoric.com/top100speechesall.html"
        target="_blank"
        >Top 100 Speeches (website)</a
      >
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10144 mb-requirement-id-10154">
        (a) Who the author was
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10144 mb-requirement-id-10155">
        (b) What the historical context was
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10144 mb-requirement-id-10156">
        (c) What difficulties the nation faced that the author wished to discuss
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10144 mb-requirement-id-10157">
        (d) What the author said
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10144 mb-requirement-id-10158">
        (e) Why the speech is important to the nation's history
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10144 mb-requirement-id-10159">
        (f) Choose a sentence or two from the speech that has significant
        meaning to you, and tell your counselor why.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-10136">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 7. </span>
      Do TWO of the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10136 mb-requirement-id-10137">
        (a) Visit a place that is listed as a National Historic Landmark or that
        is on the National Register of Historic Places. Tell your counselor what
        you learned about the landmark or site and what you found interesting
        about it. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://americasnationalparks.org/passport-to-your-national-parks/"
          target="_blank"
          >America's National Parks National Passport Program (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://www.nps.gov/index.htm" target="_blank"
          >National Park Service (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://www.archives.gov/" target="_blank"
          >National Archives (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/POC5G1gWBC0" target="_blank"
          >Does Historical Preservation Even Matter? (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.amrevmuseum.org/virtual-museum-tour?utm_source=chatgpt.com"
          target="_blank"
          >Museum of the American Revolution - Virtual Museum Tour (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10136 mb-requirement-id-10138">
        (b) Tour your state capitol building or the U.S. Capitol. Tell your
        counselor what you learned about the capitol, its function, and the
        history. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/iqz0RoNoRhE" target="_blank"
          >Capital Curiosities: Exploring Why State Capitals Aren't Always the
          Biggest Cities (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.visitthecapitol.gov/live-virtual-capitol-tour"
          target="_blank"
          >Live, Virtual US Capital Tour (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10136 mb-requirement-id-10139">
        (c) Tour a federal facility. Explain to your counselor what you saw and
        what you learned about its function in the local community and how it
        serves this nation.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-10136 mb-requirement-id-10140">
        (d) Choose a United States national monument that interests you. Using
        books, brochures, the internet (with your parent or guardian's
        permission), and other resources, find out more about the monument. Tell
        your counselor what you learned, and explain why the monument is
        important to this country's citizens. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://www.senate.gov/senators/senators-contact.htm"
          target="_blank"
          >US Senate (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://www.govtrack.us/" target="_blank">GovTrack (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://www.usa.gov/elected-officials" target="_blank"
          >USA.gov (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.commoncause.org/find-your-representative/"
          target="_blank"
          >Common Cause (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.house.gov/representatives/find-your-representative"
          target="_blank"
          >US House of Representatives (website)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-10146">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 8. </span>
      Name your representatives in the United States Congress. Write to your
      representative in Congress explaining your views on a national issue. Show
      your correspondence, along with any response you receive, to your
      counselor.
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
